commanded the attack on the right of the main position in the assault of 13&nbsp;July 1782.<ref name=odnb/>\n\nHe served in [[Third Anglo-Mysore War|the campaign of 1790]], under General Sir [[William Medows]], against [[Tipu Sultan]], attacking the fortresses of [[Dindigul]] and [[Palghaut]]. He served under [[Charles Cornwallis, 1st Marquess Cornwallis|Cornwallis]] during the campaigns of 1791\u20132, and led the [[siege of Seringapatam (1792)|siege of Seringapatam]],<ref name=\"DIB\"/> commanding the centre column in the assault of 6&nbsp;February 1792. Promoted to colonel in August, he returned to Madras in 1794.<ref name=odnb/>\n\nPromoted to major-general in 1795, he took command of the expedition against Dutch possessions in [[Ceylon]] that year. After the whole island was secured in 1796, Stuart became commander-in-chief in the same year of the forces in Madras.<ref name=odnb/><ref name=\"DIB\"/>\n\nHe was made colonel of the [[82nd&nbsp;Regiment of Foot]] in 1797,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/082-793.htm |title=82nd (The Prince of Wales's Volunteers) Regiment of Foot |publisher=regiments.ord |accessdate=30 August 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519075725/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/082-793.htm |archivedate=19 May 2006 }}</ref> transferring the following year to the [[72nd&nbsp;Regiment of Foot]], a position he held until his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/072-786.htm |title=72nd (or Duke of Albany's Own Highlanders) Regiment of Foot |publisher=regiments.org |accessdate=27 July 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070106153355/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/inf/072-786.htm |archivedate= 6 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1799 he commanded the [[Bombay Army]] in [[Fourth Anglo-Mysore War|the last war]] against Tipu, which occupied Coorg, and repulsed Tipu at [[Battle of Seedaseer|Seedaseer]] on 6&nbsp;March. On 15&nbsp;March he joined with Major General [[George Harris, 1st Baron Harris|George Harris]] (afterwards Lord Harris) before the 1799 [[Battle of Seringapatam]]<ref name=\"DIB\"/> and took charge of the operations on the northern side of the city. After its capture he  received the thanks of both [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\n==Later career and death==\nHe became commander-in-chief of the [[Madras Army]] in 1801. Promoted to lieutenant-general in 1802, he took part in the [[Second Anglo-Maratha War]] in 1803 but in 1805 returned to England in bad health. He was promoted to the rank of full general on 1 January 1812. \n\nHe died without issue at Charles Street, Berkeley Square, London, on 29 April 1815 and was buried in a vault in St. James's Chapel, Hampstead Road, London.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patrick Alexander Agnew]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Military Governor of British Ceylon]]|years=1796&ndash;1797}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Welbore Ellis Doyle]]}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-new | office }} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Officer Commanding, Ceylon]]|years=1796&ndash;1797}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Welbore Ellis Doyle]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Abercromby of Airthrey|Robert Abercromby]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bombay Army|C-in-C, Bombay Army]]|years=1797&ndash;1800}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Oliver Nicolls]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir John Braithwaite, 1st Baronet|John Braithwaite]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Madras Army|C-in-C, Madras Army]]|years=1801&ndash;1804}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Cradock, 1st Baron Howden|John Cradock]]}}\n|-\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before=Hon. Sir [[Adam Williamson]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=Colonel of the [[72nd (Highland) Regiment of Foot]] | years=1798\u20131815}}\n{{s-aft |after=Sir [[Rowland Hill, 1st Viscount Hill]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before=[[Charles Leigh (British Army officer)|Charles Leigh]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=Colonel of the [[82nd (The Prince of Wales's Volunteers) Re